## else-if Ladder

The `else-if Ladder` statement in JavaScript is used when multiple conditions need to be checked one after another. 
It is an extension of the `if-else` statement and allows the program to choose one block of code from several 
conditions. The conditions are checked from top to bottom. If the first condition is false, the program checks 
the next condition, and this process continues until a true condition is found. If none of the conditions are 
true, the `else` block executes. Only one block of code executes even if multiple conditions are true. 
The else-if ladder is commonly used in grading systems, menu-based programs, result processing systems, and 
decision-making applications. It helps organize multiple conditions in a structured way and makes programs
more flexible.

**Example:**

```javascript id="msibp6"
if(marks>=90)
console.log("Grade A");
else if(marks>=70)
console.log("Grade B");
else
console.log("Grade C");
```

### Advantages of else-if Ladder

* Handles multiple conditions easily
* Improves decision-making in programs
* Makes code organized and structured
* Suitable for complex conditions
* Easy to understand and implement

### Disadvantages of else-if Ladder

* Becomes lengthy with many conditions
* Reduces readability in large programs
* Execution may become slower due to multiple checks
* Difficult to maintain in complex applications

